metadata.name: Patched with Tartan #1
metadata.description:
Patched with Tartan is a generative patchwork made with p5.js. 
Evolving from my earlier work, "Patched", this new piece has 576 possible layout combinations, 17 new printed patterns on a choice of 7 new textile textures and two new woven fabrics with near infinite colour variation chosen from one of 13 palettes. 

This piece introduces a new tartan fabric which gives it its name. Due to the vagaries of generative art it is quite possible that a piece won't contain any tartan though so all holders of Patched with Tartan will receive free access to a brand new pure tartan token in a couple of weeks.

'2' to regenerate at 2000x2000
'3' to regenerate at 3000x3000
'r' to regenerate at window size

metadata.name: Forced Ink #25
metadata.description:
Forced Ink is an experiment in using physical forces (repulsion) to create digital artwork reminiscent of a real-world abstract painting.

Features
Color: a random color
Particle Count: between 100 and 450, equal chance
Particle Size: between 5 and 15, equal chance

metadata.name: A creative tunnel that leads to nothing #38
metadata.description:
This piece is dedicated to all those forgotten projects that have been left behind, maybe they were just simple ideas that didn't stick, or maybe full blown complex creations, never completed, never released...just stuff on the walls of a tunnel that ends into nothing.

Goodbye.

Time to move on.

#tezosartweek

metadata.name: Tumble Down Light Factory #12
metadata.description:
Tumble Down Light Factory is an interpretation of light installations & murals.

It attempts to trigger the feeling of coming up on a new block in a new city to discover an unexpected piece of art that is stories tall or entering a new room, knowing there will be a projection dominating the space with its light and color.

This is an abstract distillation of those things and those feelings.

Each composition is initially drawn to a hidden “template” canvas which is sampled and then rendered on the main canvas in various ways after applying some transforms to give it some depth (and so you can actually see it.)

Viewing in full-screen is nice. You should try it.

T : Save hidden ‘template’ image
S : Save current resolution
1 -> 5 : Save low -> high resolution

metadata.name: Diamond Fractal Fire #31
metadata.description:
Diamond Fractal Fire interposes recursively generated poetry with similarly recursive fractal imagery. Each text (unique for each mint, but always 20 sentences in length) is generated by a custom context-free grammar algorithm, fed with lists of words selected by the creator. The fractal pattern in each edition is a variation on a Koch snowflake fractal, one of the earliest fractals described by mathematicians. These fractals grow over time at varying rates, and pulse with varying color ranges using Perlin noise, eventually filling the screen.


Push `h` to save high resolution PNG and JPG images of the complete fractal pattern (takes a moment to process)
Push `s` to save PNG and JPG images of the current browser view (with current browser window dimensions and resolution)
Push `v` to begin recording canvas as a video (with current browser window dimensions), then push `v` again to save the video
Push `f` to toggle fullscreen mode
Push `p` to toggle zoom pause
Push `r` to toggle zoom reverse
Push `c` to toggle color shift pause
Push `l` to toggle low resolution mode (improves framerate)


The animation is somewhat computationally expensive, and so it runs best on contemporary laptop and desktop computers. Mobile devices and older computers may experience low frame rates. Captured video quality may vary depending on compute and browser limitations. The animation is responsive (it will adapt to any screen or window size), and resizing your browser window also will restart the animation.

Color floors and variances represent ranges for Hue using a Hue/Saturation/Brightness (HSB) color model. Velocities represent (subtle) zoom speed differences. Noise increment and start values affect the rate and variation of color shifts.

In addition to the author's code, Diamond Fractal Fire relies on the p5.js library.

metadata.name: A Clock #248
metadata.description:
This generative token is based on a project I originally coded in late 2014, possibly my first creative project in JavaScript during graduate school at NYU ITP, which has run here since then: https://rossgoodwin.com/clock

The text in this case is not generated, but rather (legally) snipped from public domain e-books on Project Gutenberg (https://gutenberg.org/), and recontextualized as a real-time clock.

The editions vary in color palette and font choice, each with unique text for every minute determined by the clock's unique hash. For nearly all word/phrase blocks in the template system, there exist 512 possible excerpts you could receive, and countless possible combinations thereof. Additionally, 16 possible color palettes, 8 possible fonts, and many bezel types will determine your clock's visual appearance.

Unlike my original 2014 iteration, I wrote this clock in Vanilla JS with zero dependencies. (Largely, that's thanks to eight additional years of programming experience.) As a result, it's faster (once loaded) and more responsive as well.
